        "code": {
          "coding": [
            {
              "system": "http://loinc.org",
              "code": "29308-4",
              "display": "Findings of Esophagogastroduodenoscopy"
            }
          ]
        },
        "subject": {
          "reference": "Patient/patient-1"
        },
        "valueString": "White light endoscopy revealed a 22 mm flat lesion in the middle esophagus. The lesion was covered with scattered leukoplakia and normal vascular network could not be seen in the lesion. Narrow-band imaging (NBI) under endoscopy revealed the lesion with an indistinct brownish area, local white penniform area and white tiny papillary surface structure. Further low and high magnifying endoscopy with NBI (ME-NBI) showed tiny irregular papillary microsurface structure with various shapes and sizes, and non-typical intraepithelial papillary capillary loops (IPCL) confined to the papillary microsurface structure. Iodine staining endoscopy showed a less-stained lesion and showed more distinct white tiny papillary surface structure than conventional white light endoscopy. Biopsy showed a low-grade intraepithelial neoplasia. Chest and abdominal CT scan revealed no abnormal lesions."
      }
    },
